      <h1>Choosing a Search Type</h1>
      <?CHUNK filename="help/contact-us.chnk" optional="1"?>
      <p> One way to control your search is to select from among a number of search types. </p>
      <p><strong><a href="search-basic.html">Basic search</a></strong> is the simplest search; it lets you look for a single word or
                     phrase in a designated area of the text. Because Basic searches are less specific, your search
                     results will be larger than for more complex searches that let you add more terms or be more specific in your search
                     query.
                  </p>
      <p><strong><a href="search-boolean.html">Boolean search</a></strong> lets you look for combinations of up to three terms or phrases
                     using Boolean connector terms (i.e., AND, OR, NOT). 
                  </p>
      <p><strong><a href="search-proximity.html">Proximity search</a></strong> lets you look for terms based on whether they occur (or do
                     not occur) within a specified distance of each other.
                  </p>
      <p><strong><a href="search-bib.html">Bibliographic search</a></strong> lets you look for words that occur in author or title or other metadata fields.
                  </p>
      <p><strong><a href="search-ww.html">Word index search</a></strong> (not available in all collections) lets you browse a concordance (an index of all words) of the collection.
                  </p>
